					<h4>Western Literary Odds & Ends</h4>
		
		<h1>Helena Book Fest Kicks Off, Krakauer Sues Over Textbooks</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 10-10-07</p>
			
							<table width="25" align="right" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
					<tr>
						<td>&nbsp;</td>
						<td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/thumbnails_feature/helenabookfest_thumb.jpg" align="right" width="153" height="150" /></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>

					
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>
				</table>
			
							<p>When is the last time you&#8217;ve thanked your favorite font for getting you through the day?&nbsp; <a target="_blank" href="http://aigacolorado.org" title="AIGA Colorado">AIGA Colorado</a> is smitten for Helvetica, and they&#8217;re throwing the font <a target="_blank" href="http://aigacolorado.org/eventdetails.aspx?eid=139" title="a 50th birthday party this week">a 50th birthday party this week</a>.&nbsp; The graphic artist organization is a sponsor of the recent documentary, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.helveticafilm.com/" title="Helvetica">Helvetica</a>, which it will screen twice on October 15, along with an appearance by the movie&#8217;s director, Gary Hustwit.&nbsp; AIGA is encouraging fans of the Swiss Modernist font to snap photos of Helvetica in action around Colorado and upload them to <a target="_blank" href="http://www.flickr.com/groups/553508@N22/" title="a Flikr photo pool">a Flikr photo pool</a>.&nbsp; There&#8217;s no word on the exact details of the birthday celebration, but I&#8217;d be disappointed if it didn&#8217;t include a carefully-lettered cake. 
</p>
<p>
The <a target="_blank" href="http://www.helenabookfest.com/" title="Helena Festival of the Book">Helena Festival of the Book</a> kicks off this week at multiple locations around Helena from October 11-14.&nbsp; They&#8217;ve got some great writers scheduled to appear, and I noticed that the female participants are particularly strong, including <a target="_blank" href="http://www.mailemeloy.com/" title="Malie Meloy">Malie Meloy</a> (the Helena native whom Granta recently included in its <a target="_blank" href="http://www.bestyoungnovelists.com/Maile-Meloy" title="Best of Young American Novelists">Best of Young American Novelists</a> issue), award-winning Montana native fiction writer <a target="_blank" href="http://hum.utah.edu/display.php?module=facultyDetails&amp;personId=124&amp;orgId=297" title="Melanie Rae Thon">Melanie Rae Thon</a>, Missoula novelist <a target="_blank" href="http://voices.cla.umn.edu/vg/Bios/entries/earling_debra_magpie.html" title="Debra Magpie Earling">Debra Magpie Earling</a>, and NewWest.net&#8217;s own Spade &amp; Spoon Editor, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/spadeandspoon/" title="Kisha Lewellyn Schlegel">Kisha Lewellyn Schlegel</a>.
</p>
<p>
Saturday&#8217;s Rocky Mountain News featured a <a target="_blank" href="http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/garden/article/0,2777,DRMN_23954_5715924,00.html" title="three-page spread by Maria Cote">three-page spread by Maria Cote</a> on writer Pam Houston and her home in Creede.&nbsp; Houston said that she bought the property with the $21,000 advance she received from her short story collection <I>Cowboys Are My Weakness</I>, and admits that she sometimes feels lonely on the ranch she&#8217;s owned for 15 years, saying, &#8220;I have to import people if I want to be among my own kind.&#8221;
</p>
<p>
Boulder-based writer Jon Krakauer is suing a textbook company for copyright infringement.&nbsp; According to <a target="_blank" href="http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/local/article/0,1299,DRMN_15_5715764,00.html" title="Sara Burnett of the Rocky Mountain News">Sara Burnett of the Rocky Mountain News</a>, &#8220;Krakauer says he gave Houghton Mifflin permission to repreint excerpts from <I>Into Thin Air</I> in no more than 40,000 copies of a ninth-grade writing book,&#8221; and according to the lawsuit, has since learned the company published over 1.2 million copies.
</p>
<p>
